John Edward: Knowledge of languages is crucial for global citizens
Scottish independent schools enjoy a reputation for academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another series of outstanding results on exams, further strengthened by individual and collective successes in sport, art, music and other community endeavors.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools want to prepare their students for further and higher education, the chosen career path and the place they have as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a tailored school curriculum, we see that modern languages are still a popular and desirable elective subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, the conversation is imprinted on his memory.
But if you speak to a man in his native language, words are imprinted in his heart.”
This is a good reminder that we should not rely solely on English when we want to establish relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s results from recent exams show that languages are at the top of the ranking with the highest rates of success in independent schools.
Sixty-eight percent of students who have studied a foreign language have achieved an excellent score.
Data collected in 74 schools members of the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS) showed that 72% of pupils achieved an excellent rating in Mandarin, while 72% of German students, 69% of French pupils and 63% of French pupils also received an excellent rating.
This proves that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as the key knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are treated as an elective subject in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere in the same way as subjects in the fields of natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission on Employment and Training found that 17% of the reasons employers are struggling to fill vacancies can be attributed to a lack of language proficiency.
Therefore, language proficiency is becoming increasingly essential in preparing young people for their future career path.
With future job opportunities requiring knowledge of languages, these skills are essential in the global world.
If a person learns another language, regardless of the career path he chooses, with such lifelong knowledge, he has a great advantage in the future.
A multilingual person who is able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries has an automatic advantage over competition.
A 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK found that 75 percent of people did not speak a foreign language well enough to be able to speak, with French being the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of respondents, or 15 percent.
Therefore, investing in language learning is important for today’s children.
With more languages, especially those from developing economies, children have better chances of finding a suitable job.
In Scotland, schools differ in the languages they teach.
Many schools are focusing on more classical modern languages, while others are teaching languages that are expected to be most important to the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interests, it will always be possible to choose a number of languages taught by experts in this field in independent schools.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that will prepare and equip children with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
In the global business environment, there is no denying that languages remain extremely important for the future of the country, so this must also be expressed in education.
In fact, modern languages should be treated as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
