Red tide news: Concentrations along the coasts of Pinellas, Manatee and Saratosa districts are decreasing
A recent report by the Florida Commission for the Protection of Fish and Wildlife (FWC) shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
The FWC Commission reported more scattered blooms in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Saratosa, Charlotte and Collier, indicating a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide extends about 130 miles from the northern coast of Pinellas County to the southern counties of Lee.
The cliffs are seen about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
The red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
Over the past week, there have been reports of intermediate concentrations in the County of Pinellas and its shoreline, low to high concentrations on the Hillsborough County shoreline, base to high concentrations in the Manatee County, base to high concentrations in the Saratosa County and its shorelines on the central and central axis.
Breath irritation continues to be reported from the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
There have been no reports of respiratory irritation from Northwest Florida in the past week.
